[1] Dysentery, earthquake related - Pakistan
Date: Mon, 17 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: International Federation of Red Cross And Red Crescent
Societies (IFRC) [edited]
<http://www.reliefweb.int/rw/RWB.NSF/db900SID/LSGZ-6HAAXA?OpenDocument>

South Asia: Earthquake Appeal No. 05EA022 Operations Update No. 5
--------------------------------------------------
Quake survivors continue to struggle with shortage of medical care,
shelter and safe water. Makeshift tent cities have reportedly sprung
up in Muzaffarabad. People burn whatever they can find to keep warm
and prepare food. Initial findings suggest that food aid appears to
be sufficient; however, the Red Cross and Red Crescent have been
alerted that food may become an issue in a few months. Limited access
and bad weather conditions are, however, limiting relief efforts to
concentrate in urban areas. Heavy rains have resulted in flooding of
tents and temporary shelters.
The UN and the Pakistani authorities estimate that only 2 percent of
the water and sanitation needs are met. There are already reporting
cases of bloody diarrhea and dysentery. Health needs are increasingly
becoming a main area of concern.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[It would be not unexpected to observe outbreaks of gastrointestinal
illnesses in the devastated area. - Mod.LL]
