[2] Cholera - Ghana (Ashanti Region)
Date: Mon, 17 Oct 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Kessben Radio [edited]
<http://www.kessbenfm.com/news/article.asp?id=305>

About 156 cases of cholera have so far been reported at the Komfo
Anokye Teaching Hospital in Kumasi. Officials have reported deaths in
as a result of delay in seeking medical attention.
Speaking on Kessben Fm's early morning show Maakye today, 17 Oct
2005, the Metro Director of Health Services, Dr. Joseph Oduro, blamed
the epidemic on food prepared and sold under unhygienic conditions
and the drinking of polluted water. Dr. Oduro cautioned the General
Public to be selective in patronizing food items and water.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Kumasi is about 255 km (158 miles) from Accra to the north and west. - Mod.LL]
******
[3] Cholera - Ghana (Greater Accra Region)
Date: Fri, 14 Oct 2005
From: Pablo Nart <pablo12@hotPOP.com>
Source: Ghanaweb [edited]
<http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=92155>

The Greater Accra Regional Directorate of the Ghana Health Service on
Fri, 14 Oct 2005, warned the public about reported cases of cholera
in parts of the region and asked them to report cases of frequent
loose or watery stools and vomiting to the nearest clinic or hospital.
A statement signed by Dr Edward Antwi, Senior Medical Officer,
advised the public to maintain personal and environmental hygiene by
washing of hands with soap and water before eating and after visiting
the toilet.
It said vegetables and fruits should be washed properly and with
clean water and there should be proper disposal of liquid and solid waste.
The GHS advised the public to avoid buying or eating cold and
uncovered food, while food should be eaten warm.
--
Pablo Nart
<pablo12@hotPOP.com>
[No numbers of cases are given in this report. - Mod.LL]
