[6] Cholera - Belgium ex Turkey
Date: Wed, 13 Oct 2005
From: Per-Arne Parment <Per-Arne.Parment@sblvaccines.se>
Source: Eursosurveillance [edited]
<http://www.eurosurveillance.org/ew/2005/051013.asp#2>

2 confirmed and 4 probable cases of cholera have been reported in
Belgian tourists returning from travel to Turkey. On 22 Sep 2005, the
Gezondheidsinspectie (Health Inspectorate) in Antwerp was notified of
the isolation of _Vibrio cholerae_ in a stool sample from a
62-year-old woman. She was admitted to hospital in Antwerp on 17 Sep
2005 immediately after returning from a trip to Turkey, with watery
diarrhea, dehydration and renal failure. The clinical picture was
initially unclear because she had undergone stomach surgery to treat
cancer not long before the tour. The patient was admitted to hospital
for 4 days and was treated with quinolones. Further testing confirmed
infection with _V. cholerae__O1 biotype El Tor, serotype Inaba.
After notification of this case, an investigation was begun to
collect epidemiological information, ascertain any other potential
cases, identify the source and coordinate control measures. All tour
group members were interviewed about potential exposures during the trip.
A 2nd female patient had contracted severe gastrointestinal symptoms
on 18 Sep 2005. She was treated as an outpatient. A stool culture was
also positive for _V. cholerae_ O1. She was treated with quinolones
and recovered. 4 other patients contracted severe gastroenteritis
shortly after their return. They were seen by their general
practitioners and were treated with symptomatic therapy. Stool
cultures were performed after these patients had recovered and did
not grow _V. cholerae_. All patients recovered after 4 days. No
secondary cases were detected. The attack rate for the tour group was
6/8 (75 percent).
The tour group had traveled around west Turkey on a 14-day package
tour. Group members were aged between 58 and 68 years. They used a
private bus, and at the end of their trip, they took an internal
flight from Ankara to Istanbul.
During the journey they stayed at different hotels and visited
Istanbul, Bursa, Efeze, Affrodisias, Pamukkale, Kusadasi, Antalya,
Cappadocia, Ilhara and Ankara. They ate in several small restaurants
and also ate food bought at markets and shops. During the internal
flight, a salad was served.
Control measures
----------------
All tour group members were informed of the risks, and advised to
contact their general practitioner and provide a stool sample.
General practitioners were advised about treatment and follow-up.
Patients were advised to limit their contacts and to apply hygienic
measures to prevent further transmission. Patients were not
automatically admitted to hospital nor systematically treated with
antibiotics. The WHO, the Turkish health authorities and the European
Early Warning and Response System (EWRS) were informed immediately
after detection of the cases.
Discussion
----------
Cholera is an acute bacterial enteric disease caused by an infection
with _V. cholerae_, serogroup O1 or O139. _V. cholerae_ includes 2
biotypes -- the classical type and El Tor type. Each biotype has 3
serotypes (Inaba, Ogawa, and rarely Hikojima). Cholera may be present
in an asymptomatic state, as a mild disease or as the typical
syndrome characterized by a sudden onset and profuse, painless,
watery diarrhea. The incubation period varies from a few hours to 5
days and patients are infectious while they have diarrhea and up to 7
days after (1, 2).
Databases of cholera cases reported to the WHO last recorded cholera
cases in Turkey in 1977, and no data was supplied from 1978-1992. To
date, there have been no other recent cases of cholera reported from
Turkey (3).
Only the 2 patients confirmed to have cholera were treated with
antibiotics. The other patients received symptomatic treatment and
recovered quickly. The patients had only a few contacts, and were not
working on or participating in activities which could have
facilitated secondary transmission.
The attack rate was rather high (75 percent). A 7th patient developed
minimal diarrhea 5 days after return from Turkey but was not
considered as a probable case. The high attack rate probably
represents a high infective dose and there could potentially be other
cases in Turkish residents or in visiting tourists. There are
unofficial reports of cholera outbreaks in countries in the region
surrounding Turkey, such as Iran, Tajikistan and Afghanistan (4, 5, 6).
1. Hawker J, Begg N, Blair I, et al: Cholera. In: Communicable
Disease Control Handbook. Oxford: Blackwell Science Ltd 2001.
2. Heyman DL: Control of Communicable Disease Manual. Washington: APHA; 2004
3. WHO: Cholera. Wkly Epidemiol Rec 2005: 80: 261-8.
(<http://www.who.int/wer/2005/wer8031.pdf>)
4. Cholera, diarrhea & dysentery update 2005 (36). In: ProMED-mail
[online]. Boston US: International Society for Infectious Diseases,
archive no. 20050916.2732, 16 Sep 2005. (<http://www.promedmail.org>)
5. Cholera-like illness - Tajikistan: RFI. In: ProMED-mail [online].
Boston US: International Society for Infectious Diseases, archive no.
20050803.2254, 3 Aug 2005. (<http://www.promedmail.org>)
6. WHO Communicable Disease Surveillance and Response: Cholera in
Afghanistan. Disease Outbreak News, 21 June 2005
(<http://www.who.int/csr/don/2005_06_21/en/index.html>)
[De Schrijver K (<koen.deschrijver@wvc.vlaanderen.be>), Boeck H, Top G, et al]
--
Per-Arne Parment
<Per-Arne.Parment@sblvaccines.se>
[ProMED thanks Per-Arne Parment for this contribution. It appears
that endemic cholera still exists in Turkey. - Mod.LL]
